rows.field_308456: Assists their immediate business analysis supervisor and seniors with assigned tasks and responsibilities.

The Business Analyst collaborates with stakeholders to analyze and document business processes for the system under development, to define functional requirements and high-level features, to elaborate on the details of the software project and requirements in order to establish the project's direction, and to assist in its implementation.

Senior Business Analysts are responsible for supervising the rest of the business analysts while maintaining the same responsibilities as base-level business analysts. Furthermore, this role is considered an expert in their field.
Assists their immediate quality assurance supervisor and seniors with assigned tasks and responsibilities.

A Quality Assurance Engineer creates tests to identify software defects prior to a product's launch. These tests entail additional responsibilities, such as developing and running new tests and communicating their results to stakeholders, with whom you will collaborate to fix program bugs or problems.

Senior Quality Assurance Engineers are responsible for supervising the rest of the QA engineers while maintaining the same responsibilities as base-level Quality Assurance Engineers. Furthermore, this role is considered an expert in their field.
Assists their immediate programming supervisor and seniors with assigned tasks and responsibilities.

Software Engineers are responsible for implementing engineering principles in the development of software. Their responsibilities include analyzing and modifying existing software as well as designing, building, and testing end-user applications that meet user requirements  all via software programming languages.

Senior Software Engineers are responsible for supervising the rest of the software engineers while maintaining the same responsibilities as base-level engineers. Furthermore, this role is considered an expert in their field.
Assists the company's recruiter in posting jobs and in sorting job applicants.

fields.name: Review ID
fields.formula:
upper( 
  concat( 
    "R", 
    left( 
      regex_replace( 
        field("Review period"), 
        "(/|-|:|\s|\t)", 
        "" 
      ), 
      6 
    ), 
    field("Employee ID number"), 
    "-", 
    row_id() 
  ) 
)

fields.name: Rating average
fields.formula:
(field('Attendance and timekeeping') + 
field('Creativity and innovation') + 
field('Problem solving and resourcefulness') + 
field('Communication skills') + 
field('Interpersonal skills') + 
field('Customer experience') + 
field('Work ethic') + 
field('Productivity') + 
field('Accountability') + 
field('Improvements and achievements')) / 10

fields.name: Rating total (max 50)
fields.formula:
field('Attendance and timekeeping') + 
field('Creativity and innovation') + 
field('Problem solving and resourcefulness') + 
field('Communication skills') + 
field('Interpersonal skills') + 
field('Customer experience') + 
field('Work ethic') + 
field('Productivity') + 
field('Accountability') + 
field('Improvements and achievements')

views.name: Create new employee review
views.title: Employee Performance Review Form
views.description: Companies and organizations regularly conduct staff performance appraisals. This is essential to managing teams and harmony in the workplace. These staff evaluations are traditionally performed quarterly, biannually, and/or annually.
views.submit_action_message: Thank you for completing the Staff Performance Review Form. Please get back to the Reviews Grid under the Reviews Table of the Performance Review Database to validate your recent review and attach review files under the Supporting Documents field of your new record.

field_options.description: Please type in a new and unique review ID for this appraisal. You may apply your organization's standard to avoid duplicates. Example: Sales-BR099-2022/Q3

field_options.name: Employee ID No.
field_options.description: Please select the employee ID number for the employee currently being reviewed. You may refer to the Employees Table and Employee Gallery for employee reference. Select or use Search to find the employee number for this review.
Please select the appropriate review period for this assessment.

Attendance and reliable time reporting are important factors in evaluating an individual's performance because these things are important in most professions.Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

This is important in the workplace because it allows for new ideas and creative thought. In a modern, forward-thinking company, creative thinking and new ideas are highly encouraged.Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

When you solve a problem, you figure out what caused it, look for possible solutions, prioritize and choose between them, and choose the most efficient solution.Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

In a dynamic work environment, communication is one of the most important parts of how things work together. It's important to be able to communicate well with supervisors, coworkers, and clients in a lot of different businesses. Communication that is clear makes people more comfortable with each other, which makes them more likely to share and exchange ideas. It also makes everyone more productive because it bridges the gap between departments and helps everyone work together. Rating Scales: 5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

People who have good interpersonal skills have a lot of different skills that are often needed for many jobs. While some people are born with good interpersonal skills, for others, they can be learned through experience and knowledge, and they can also be taught.Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

When you focus on your customers and give them good service, you can build long-term relationships with them. Employees need to learn skills that will help customers have a better experience. Customer can either be internal or external  project stakeholders can be viewed as customers or clients as well. Rating Scales: 5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

There are a lot of things that make up an employee's work ethic, like working hard, being honest, and treating others with respect. By looking into an employee's ethics and morals, you can stop bad and demotivating behavior from spreading in the workplace.Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

Employees must remain productive during work hours in order to contribute to the company's goals. Likewise, productivity is a good indicator of an employee's engagement level. Productivity is determined by the quality and quantity of work performed by an employee in comparison to the standards established by the employer.Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

It's important for employees to try to be responsible for their work and own up to mistakes they make. They should also do their best to fix them as best they can. This makes efficient use of time and shows that an employee is trustworthy. Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).

Typically, employees have room for growth. It is also essential to account for and recognize employee accomplishments, whether they are related to project milestones or work initiatives.Rating Scales:5 Stars = FE (Far Exceeds); 4 Stars = EX (Exceeds Expectations); 3 Stars = ME (Meets Expectations); 2 Stars = DR (Development Required); 1 Star = IR (Improvement Required).
This section is a summary of this assessment and, at the same time, allows the reviewer to include employee recommendations based on this employee's assessment.
